segments.text: Remembering those things.

When they were going from Chihuahua to Adama disguised as peasants, my father had told my mother that if they ever got stopped on the way, that if they asked any questions, they were going to visit relatives at Adama.
And after a while of traveling, they got stopped from some armed men.
They were asked, where are you going?
And she said, well, we are going to
Chihuahua, I mean the Aldamara, he's a relative.
And my father, he was, had a sarap that was wrapped around him, you know, so they couldn't see his face, you know.
And then they asked him, well, what's wrong with him?
You know, they meant why he doesn't say, he says something.
Uh-huh.
My brother, because he's got a wound in his leg.
Oh, boy.
Oh, my God.
And then what happened?
Well, then my father just went up and said, well, I was out hunting two or three years ago, and I shot myself in the leg because I don't know too much about firearms.
And they just laughed, you know.
And I said, well.
Let him go.
And after that, my father really got mad at my mother.
Hurt them?
Yeah.
And he got shot?
Yeah, and he had a wound.
Well, he was scared.
I mean, he always knows.
Every time she saw a man like that, she remembered what she went through and she forgot what she was supposed to say.
Poor thing.
She was afraid of your father, wasn't she?
She was.
She was.
She used to tell us, I don't know why I married that man.
I didn't love him, but I had to marry him or else.
Yes, I remember the time that, she told me about it, she did.
I mean, my mother didn't tell me too many things about his life, you know.
My mother, she says that the doctor, they operated on him three or four times, the same woman.
And he told the doctors that he wanted his leg saved, but tried.
But Dr. Hefner, Chihuahua, told him the leg had to come off because it was going to be useless.
It was going to be just in his way.
And my mother told him that he warned the doctor, he said, if you cut my leg off, I'm going to kill you.
The doctor, he didn't believe him, too.
Because, you know, he's a patient.
And one of his friends told him, you'd better do what he says.
Don't cut his leg off, because, don't kill him, because if he wants his leg, let him keep his leg.
So they let him keep his leg, but it was no good to him.
He was always limping, wasn't he?
No.
Remember Chester?
Chester?
Gunsmoke?
That's the way my father had his leg, stiff.
He could never bend it.
He could never bend it.
Had he been a foot soldier or did he, was he a cavalry?
He was in the cavalry.
He had a horse.
Did you show her that picture with all the things in his head and everything?
Yeah.
He was proud to be one of, to be this man.
They were all crazy.
They were all crazy.
Well, tell about your father wanting your mother to go to Chihuahua before you were born.
Well, I don't know what it is.
I guess he planned on going back as soon as he could.
And he wanted me to be born in Chihuahua.
And the only reason that my mother, she was afraid that they did.
Trin would be stopping, and one of the relatives talked to my father, and she got to agree, you know, to be born here in El Paso.
But your parents were born in Chihuahua?
Oh, I mean, were they married?
They were married in Chihuahua.
In Chihuahua, they were married in Chihuahua.
Yeah, they never dreamed of ever coming to the United States.
They never did.
But since that incident when the Morgia was after him and wanted him there alive, he had to leave the country.
And I guess you could call him a refugee.
Well, how come my parents, I mean my father, my family and my father, since 1910, they were here.
They start this because I heard from my aunt in Santa Rita,
They had to leave the ranch, because they were near there, see?
And they were taking all the girls.
So they just left since 9th and 10th, and they never returned.
So at that time, everything was happening by .
That's .
I don't know.
Because I remember when my aunt was telling me about Camaro, the people that he burned over there in Camaro, and the hoyo, you know, loyote, grandote.
Have you been to Camaro?
No.
There's a big hole.
I don't know if they fixed it already or not, but where he burned all the people.
Children?
I don't know.
I think that's just a story.
It isn't.
It isn't.
Were they alive when he burned them?
Oh, yes.
He put some, what's it, petroleum?
He burned them alive.
Why?
I don't know.
Because he was crazy.
I don't know.
Was this Villa?
Villa.
Don't you remember?
I don't know.
You can ask my Tio Rodolfo.
He was there.
They were there.
Is he still alive?
Oh, yes.
He's an old man now.
You can tell they were there.
I know that they used to hang a lot of people.
I know about the hanging.
Yeah.
Because there's a tree over there in the Mera Placita, Camargo, where they just put the ropes.
Well, when I was a youngster and I used to go to Chihuahua, we used to go to the river.
And they used to show me the trees, the tall, big, old, tall trees.
where they used to hang people from.
Did they say why they hung them?
Well, the people that were hanging there were villistas.
And they tell me,
that they hung a lot of innocent people just because they looked villista.

I mean, they actually didn't know for sure if they were villista, but there were so many people, you know, that they'd pick them out on the street or went to knock on the door of a house, and whoever answered there, he looked like a villista.
So they rang him out.
I mean, they were just ignorant people like he is.
Maybe they would have been used to that.
Maybe they were only passing by him.
I don't know an old man that retired from mountains.
He didn't go to Juarez for about 25 years.
And this is what happened to him because he told me about it.
He was already living here and working here in El Paso.
And he was from Zacatecas.
In fact, he knew my relatives down there.
He said that one time he went to Juarez when they had this, the attack Juarez, remember?
Well, he went to Juarez and he was just the bystander that picked him out.
And they put him in between some soldiers and took him down to the guarnicin or whatever you call it, I mean the cuartel or garrison.
And they interrogated him and they asked him a lot of questions.
And he said the way it looked, they were ready to shoot him.
He was scared and stiff, you know.
And then
a man there in Juarez that knows him by, well, I think it's, he used to own Balderas Bullring.
He called him Gonzales.
He was going by.
He says, Rafael, what are you doing there?
Come over here.
He says, tell these people who I am.
Tell them where I live.
He says, you know, he told them who he was and where he lived, so let him go.
And as soon as he got back to El Paso, that was it.
He went back to the Quarters for about 25 years.
In fact, I think he started going to the Quarters when I started working at Momsen's.
Do people talk much about the battles that were fought near here?
Well, no.
I remember that my mother and father, we must have been living in south El Paso.
Right there, along the river, we had American forces, you know, just guarding the river.
But they tell me that they could hear the fighting in the water, and then a stray bullet would come across and hit somebody over here, just accidentally.
Did your father or your mother ever talk about why he joined with B?
I mean, did he believe he was fighting for anything?
Believe in the revolution?
Yes, he did.
He did.
My father used to tell me that.
In fact, at first, you know, he thought it was the greatest thing that could have happened to Mexico.
But as he got older,
And the song was happening in Mexico.
He used to say, put it this way.
And then he'd say, you know, a word, you know.
In other words, they fought the battles, but some other people came over and took over.
They took credit for what they did, in other words.
That's what he meant.
that they fought for freedom, for democracy or whatever they call it then.
But some other people came over and took over and it was the same old story again.
Just one party rule.
He didn't believe in that after that.
He thought maybe there would be a freer elections and all that.
But after so many years, he got a little, well, in fact, oh, he was already sick.
He was, you could say, the last few years of his life.
He was disappointed, in other words, with what had happened.
Well, what, because of the one party, or...?
Yes, because he used to say, somos mismos.
He meant, you know, that nobody else had a chance to run against the...
Well, what about land for the poor and some of the other idea, or land for the villages and some of the other ideas of the revolution?
Did he ever talk about those?
Yes, he liked the idea.
In fact, he got a... That's how he got his land, or his land near south of the forest.
I don't remember how he called it.
Alaristas or something like that.
Alaristas?
Mm-hmm.
But like I say, overall, he wasn't too proud that it was just a one party system in Mexico.
He thought that

Well, I guess after he was in the United States and so on, the way things were run, you know, he never voted or anything like that, but he used to, you know, sort of, he used to tell me it was sort of fair elections, in other words.
Because in Mexico, a year ahead, you can know who's going to be elected.
Mm-hmm.
And he didn't like that idea at all.
Well, what do you think about... Did he talk about life being any better in Mexico or the standard of living being higher or anything like that?
No, he was disappointed.
He was disappointed.
The poor stayed poor.
And only the, I guess you could call them the smart, got rich off of the poor.
He was not for that.
In fact, he wasn't a very well educated man, but he was smart.
Like I tell my boys, I wish I hadn't had half the rings my father had because
Anything he did, I mean, for instance, he was a cripple.
And I remember, because I was just a youngster, he bought a car.
And he couldn't drive it because of his disability.
So he hired a man to drive for him.
And one time, he couldn't get the man, or I don't know, he fired him or something like that, and he said, well, I'm going to drive the car.
And my mom said, oh, you can't drive a car with that blade.
I said, I'm going to drive it.
So he made a contraction where he, you know, it was a driver car.
And he was a very good driver.
He was a very good driver.
And at first,
Something was going wrong with the car, so he hired a mechanic to fix it.
Pretty soon, he said, well, I'm not going to pay anybody just to do that.
So he started working on that car.
He used to break it all down, tear it apart completely, and then assemble it again.
And you know, I mean, I can't do it.
I can tear things apart, but I can't put them together again.
And he used to...
do a mechanic job very well, carpentry work, build anything, you know, things like that, he was pretty capable.
Did he ever talk about any of the battles or any of the things that he did while he was fighting for Villa?
No, like I said before, he never did talk to me too much about when he was a soldier, about his life when he was a soldier.
Did he ever talk with anybody else about it?
I don't think so.
I was just thinking that if I ever heard conversations with him.
No?
I don't remember him.
I don't remember.
You know what he liked to do when he was in the crowd, conversations, something like that?
He used to learn a lot of poems.
He used to recite, like to recite poems and sing.
He used to play guitar and used to sing.
Do you remember what songs he sang?
Oh, a lot of those Pajarito Barranqueo, La Edita.
He used to sing a lot about Mexico.
I forget the names of the songs.
I don't have a good memory of the names of the songs.
They used to sing a lot.
And in fact, my father, he was always a laughable party.
In other words, he always got invited to parties because he'd carry his guitar with him and he'd always have him sing.
He had a good voice.
Or say poems and all.
I think one poem that I never forgot, and it's a very small one.
What is it?
It's called En Esta Vida Es Y Sillanto, Los Hombres Andres Mos.
Somos los locos que en romera vamos para el camposanto.
Because it got a lot of meaning.
Yes, it does.
And that's the only one that I ever learned that I never forgot a meaning.
But I used to say a lot of poems like that.
long, and his favorite play was the Juan Tenorio.
He used to act it out.
In fact, in the party, you know, he'd get a cast of, he'd have a few beers, a few drinks, you know, get a broomstick, you know, and he'd act out the Juan Tenorio in the nest and all that.
No, he was at that time.
He had a very good memory, I mean, for him.
He learned by himself.
And he knew how to write when he was little.
He knew how to write, read.
Had he gone to school at all?
Oh, I think he had about three years of school.
He had about three years of school.
Because that's what happened over there.
They didn't even know how to write and read or nothing.
But I was thinking about my father.
Do you know how to write?
Yeah, I know how to write.
And your uncle, when he says, Lado?
No.
My family, they all did.
You know how to write in Spanish and English.
I see.
Can you mention?
What is this?
Well, I guess it's a
Nothing strange about it.
The people, you know, during the frontier days, I mean, they didn't go to school, and still a lot of people were self-educated.
That's right.
